<subSubSection box="[151,933,978,1005]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,2013]" box="[151,933,978,1005]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,165,978,1004]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">1</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Erichson, 1843: 249" authorityName="Erichson" authorityPageNumber="249" authorityYear="1843" box="[179,525,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[179,293,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Conotelus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Erichson, W. F." box="[300,525,979,1005]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="225 - 363" refId="ref104407" refString="Erichson, W. F. (1843) Versuch einer systematischen Eitheilung der Nitidularien. Germar Zeitung fur Entomologie, 34, 225 - 363." type="journal article" year="1843">Erichson, 1843: 249</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
—Nearctic and Neotropical regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1014,1040]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Body subcylindrical and very narrow with convex both upper and below surface. Labrum transverse and without trace of median suture. Abdominal segments telescopically conjoined and following segment more or less retracted into previous one; articulation between ventrites and laterosternites forming arc in cross-section (but not forming sharp fold). Male anal sclerite very long and with proximal parts of its ventral edges closed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1158,1184]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Comparison</emphasis>
. The new tribe has clear differences from other genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirejtshuk et Audisio" authorityYear="1986" box="[977,1091,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cillaeinae">Cillaeinae</taxonomicName>
defined in the above diagnosis. The most prominent features of the conotelins are in the structure of their abdomen, 
<typeStatus box="[1089,1137,1195,1221]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">type</typeStatus>
of intersegmental junction and peculiar male anal sclerite, which are very different from those not only in all other cillaeines, about also in all other nitidulids. The body of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[590,704,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[590,704,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather convex from below and more or less convex from above (up to at most only slightly subflattened), but, in contrast to other convex nitidulids, the conotelin abdomen has not any sharp compressed fold along ventrite and laterosternite. 
<bibRefCitation author="Murray, A." box="[884,1110,1338,1365]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="211 - 414" refId="ref107402" refString="Murray, A. (1864) Monograph of the family of Nitidulariae. Part I. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, 24 (3), 211 - 414." type="journal article" year="1864">Murray (1864: 256)</bibRefCitation>
put 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[1162,1276,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1162,1276,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="Murray, 1864" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1864" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Ctilodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1343,1436,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Ctilodes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Murray, A." box="[151,303,1375,1401]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="211 - 414" refId="ref107402" refString="Murray, A. (1864) Monograph of the family of Nitidulariae. Part I. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, 24 (3), 211 - 414." type="journal article" year="1864">Murray, 1864</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Stephens, 1829" authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[357,675,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Carpophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[357,497,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Carpophilus</emphasis>
Stephens, 1829
</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName authority="Murray, 1864" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1864" box="[804,1088,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Urophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[804,926,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Urophorus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Murray, A." box="[933,1088,1375,1401]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="211 - 414" refId="ref107402" refString="Murray, A. (1864) Monograph of the family of Nitidulariae. Part I. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, 24 (3), 211 - 414." type="journal article" year="1864">Murray, 1864</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kirejtshuk, 1990 a" authorityName="Kirejtshuk" authorityYear="1990" box="[1099,1432,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Anophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1099,1222,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Anophorus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kirejtshuk, A. G." box="[1229,1432,1375,1401]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="92 - 127" refId="ref105805" refString="Kirejtshuk, A. G. (1990 a) [New taxa of the Nitidulidae) of the Eastern Hemisphere. Part 4.] Tрudы ZooЛogiciсKogo iнсtituta РAН [Proceedings of Zoological Institute of Russian Academy of Sciences], 257, 92 - 127. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1990">Kirejtshuk, 1990a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Murray, 1864" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1864" box="[151,391,1411,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Nitops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,224,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Nitops</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Murray, A." box="[234,391,1411,1437]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="211 - 414" refId="ref107402" refString="Murray, A. (1864) Monograph of the family of Nitidulariae. Part I. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, 24 (3), 211 - 414." type="journal article" year="1864">Murray, 1864</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Motschulsky, 1858" authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1858" box="[405,788,1410,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Ecnomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[405,561,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Ecnomorphus</emphasis>
Motschulsky, 1858
</taxonomicName>
, etc.) in the group “ 
<emphasis box="[1022,1226,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Anguste-fimbriata</emphasis>
”, considering that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[151,265,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is intermediate between the genera “ 
<emphasis box="[693,856,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Late-fimbriata</emphasis>
” (mostly 
<taxonomicName box="[973,1069,1447,1473]" pageId="11" pageNumber="30" rank="tribe" tribe="Cillaeini">Cillaeini</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1079,1140,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">s. str.</emphasis>
) and “ 
<emphasis box="[1220,1424,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Anguste-fimbriata</emphasis>
” (mostly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Kirejtshuk" authorityYear="1986" box="[247,411,1483,1510]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carpophilinae">Carpophilinae</taxonomicName>
). Indeed, the carpophiline abdomen has the somewhat convex upper sclerotized surface, however, the sides of its “ventrites” turn on the upper surface without visible laterosternites (this peculiarity in the structure of the carpophiline abdomen also represents a rather modified condition and, therefore, the similarity of abdomens of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Kirejtshuk &amp; Kovalev, 2022" authorityName="Kirejtshuk &amp; Kovalev" authorityYear="2022" box="[382,500,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="trib. nov." tribe="Conotelini">Conotelini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[509,621,1590,1617]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="tribe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[509,614,1590,1617]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">trib. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Kirejtshuk" authorityYear="1986" box="[679,838,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carpophilinae">Carpophilinae</taxonomicName>
are certainly convergent). It is difficult to say if the carpophiline laterosternites are completely reduced or the initial suture between the ventrites and laterosternites are completely fused (become not traced). And as a result, it is impossible to be sure in a strict homology of the upper sclerotized sides externally from abdominal pleurites of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Kirejtshuk &amp; Kovalev, 2022" authorityName="Kirejtshuk &amp; Kovalev" authorityYear="2022" box="[823,941,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="trib. nov." tribe="Conotelini">Conotelini</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[948,1058,1698,1725]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="tribe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[948,1051,1698,1725]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">trib. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Kirejtshuk" authorityYear="1986" box="[1112,1274,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carpophilinae">Carpophilinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,2013]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The labrum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[365,479,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[365,479,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
looks like transverse or slightly curved monolyte stripe without any trace of a median suture. The generalized condition of this structure represents two lobes and it has in many groups a trend to close these lobes and in these cases the labrum obtains monolyte outline with a more or less traced suture or remnants of it. In very rare cases among cillaeines the suture between labral lobes became not visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,978,2013]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Many cillaeines have abdomen with long intersegmental membrane between segments and this circumstance conditions a comparatively great variability in length of abdomen of many species (but not so great as in staphylinids with telescopically folding abdominal segments). Nevertheless, the sclerotized base of abdominal segments of most cillaeines are located at most closely to apex of previous segment, while the abdominal segments of species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[151,265,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are frequently joined telescopically (at least in museum specimens). Among nitidulids somewhat similar condition can be observed in the last abdominal segment of carpophilines. Finally, the ultimate abdominal segment in the new tribe is extremely long and the male anal sclerite of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1843" box="[867,981,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Conotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,981,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Conotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in conrast to all other nitidulids, is also abnormally long and its ventral lobes are strongly enlarged and forming a long tube for movement of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,513,366,393]" box="[151,513,366,393]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,513,366,393]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Cillaeine genera incertae sedis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
